How Biometry Invaders Our Lives
Do you finish typing passwords to access your smartphone or pay your purchases?
American, French or Japanese researchers predict a future where we will be recognized by biometric sensors of phones and computers.
Bernard Didier, Deputy Director General of Morpho, even believes that "the century will be biometric".
Only biometry will ensure the identity of a person performing transactions in a universe as transverse and transnational as the Internet.
The organizations dedicated to the protection of privacy confirm this desire for biometry, but worry about it.
Only in 2011 and France, the National Commission for Computer Science and Freedoms has authorized 774 systems for the recognition of fingerprints, the form of the hand or the venous network of the hand in companies, administrations, canteens...
"Everyone will soon be able to be identified, anywhere and at any time," justin Brookman, responsible for the privacy of consumers in the CDT (Centre for Democracy and Technology), in Washington.
The reasons for such optimism, in one another, and pessimism, in the other?
Biometry will be based on new techniques, which will enable new services to citizens and consumers.
Today, in France, the most commonly used biometric data are fingerprints, hand contours and the venous network of the palm or fingers.
But each of these techniques has its own constraints.
"For example, some people who work concrete have very damaged fingers and their fingerprints are unreadable," says Philippe Robin, Technical Director of the Identification Field at Thales Communications & Security.
And the collection, as well as the verification of the venous network and the hand contour, imply a voluntary and precise gesture of individuals.
It is both a security - we cannot capture this data to their unawares - and a disadvantage: the procedure must sometimes be repeated and therefore take time.
As a result, research has been carried out for some 20 years on other approaches, such as facial recognition or iris (the colored part of the eye).
Thanks to increased sensor accuracy and computer computing capacity required for data analysis, these techniques become operational.
The accuracy of facial recognition has been multiplied by ten over the last five years, calculated Cyrille Bataller, Director of Accent R&D laboratories in Europe.
With our help, the United Kingdom and Holland have deployed automatic border posts using facial recognition.
It is now possible to identify a moving face or iris.
"Today we are doing research on voice recognition or how to walk with sound sensors, but we need a quiet environment," said Sridhar Iyengar, Director of Security Research at Intel Labs.
Unique and infallible marker, DNA also arouses hopes and concerns.
"In the current state of knowledge, it can be regarded as the ultimate biometric data," confirms Sophie Vulliet-Tavernier, Director of Studies, Innovation and Prospective at CNIL.
But DNA analysis is still very long and very expensive.
NEC offers judicial police services a voucher of €90,000 to analyse DNA samples at the place of crime and in an hour.
The uses of biometry are divided into two groups: identification (recognizing one person among others) and authentication (make sure that the person is the person it claims to be).
The identification has so far involved the issue of identity papers: biometric elements (prints, photo, iris) must be compared with information that the state has on all already fixed citizens.
This makes it possible to ensure that a person does not attempt to usurp someone else's identity.
This principle of comparison may have other applications.
NEC thus offers VIP recognition at the entrance of a hotel or a store.
"We are recovering the images of surveillance cameras and comparing them to photos of celebrities who move freely on the Internet," explains Dany Nassif, in charge of commercial development for biometric identification solutions at NEC France.
Other use: take a picture of someone who tails in a store, follow its progression through facial recognition and calculate the waiting time.
Authentication initially involved physical access (frontier, protected premises, canteens...) or logic (opening a computer).
More recently, the presence control has been added.
"A biometric pointer avoids the phenomenon of the partner who points for another," explains Cyrille Battaller, of Accenture.
But, increasingly, authentication will also concern transactions, in particular those made from devices connected to the Internet.
In Japan, it is already possible to withdraw money from certain distributors by introducing his card and placing his hand on a biometric player: this gesture replaces the secret code strike.
A similar technique is tested in Villeneuve-d'Ascq and Angoulême by the Natural Security company in partnership with banks and brands of the large distribution: when paying in store with its bank card, the customer does not type his code, but introduces his finger into a reader that scans the veins.
The experiment is planned to last six months.
If it is conclusive, biometric readers could soon arrive at French traders.
Tips to reassure users
There are three ways to make biometry attractive to the general public.
The first is to explain that it can save time.
"If, thanks to biometry, a client remains in cash thirty seconds less, it is appreciable," explains the director of a large area.
The second is to offer personalized services: in a few years, a voice server will be able to recognize your voice and offer you custom options.
And finally, make sure by highlighting the precautions taken to protect databases.
"The fingerprints are stored on a first server; the identities of the people are in a second base: the correlation between the two numbers is encrypted and stored in a highly secure box, which is blocked if you try to move it," says Philippe Robin of Thales.
However, due to a lack of in-depth studies, it is impossible to know whether these speeches really convince users.
Privacy specialists continue to worry.
"The progress of facial recognition, the multiplication of surveillance cameras and the huge amount of photos available on Facebook, Flickr or Picasa, made me fear the worst: a generalized surveillance," said Andrew Patrick of the Office of the Privacy Commissioner in Canada.
