Scientists have just highlighted how the movements of a dog's tail are related to its mood.
Previous studies had revealed that happy dogs moved their tail further to the right (from the dog's point of view), while nerve dogs moved it further to the left.
But now scientists say that dogs can detect and respond to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trent, said: "Everyone knows that in humans, the left side and the right side of the brain are involved differently in the stimuli that awaken positive or negative emotions."
Here, we tried to see what was in other species.
He added that just as in man, in dogs the right side of the brain was responsible for the movement to the left and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played a different role in emotions.
To learn more about how dogs react to the movements of tails disordered by other dogs, researchers followed animals watching movies in which other dogs appeared.
They measured the heart rate of the animals and analyzed their behaviour.
It will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes goes on one side and sometimes on the other.
Professor Vallortigara explained: "We have presented to dogs films where other dogs were in the picture – either a naturalist version or a silhouette to avoid any other confusion factor – and we have been able to trade the tail movement and present it as going more left or right."
When the animals saw a dog without expression stir the tail to the right (from the point of view of the dog that removes the tail), they remained perfectly relaxed.
But when they spotted a tail mainly turning to the left (again again from the dog's point of view that removes the tail), their heart rate accelerated and they looked anxious.
Professor Vallortigara said that he did not think the dogs would deliberately communicate with each other through these movements.
Rather, he thinks that dogs know by experience which movements they should or should not worry about.
He added: "If you meet other dogs several times and if you notice that, most of the time, the movement of their tails to one side is associated with a more friendly attitude and that the right side leads to a less friendly attitude, you will react according to this experience."
Researchers indicate that results could enable owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand their animals' emotions.
Canine behaviour expert John Bradshaw, an invited professor at the University of Bristol School of Veterinary Sciences, explained that this was not the first study to examine the importance of the left and right in the canine species.
Last year, a team from Lincoln University discovered that the dogs turned their heads to the left when they looked at an aggressive dog and right when it was a happy dog.
And in another scientific study carried out by Victoria University in Canada, he said: "The dogs went more easily to a robot dog when their tail moved to the left rather than to the right, rather than to become anxious – the opposite of what appears in the Italian study."
He indicated that differences could come from the fact that dogs who participated in the various studies did not fully consider animals of films or robot dogs as dogs.
A study on how dogs react to real dogs could be useful, he explained.
"Although many elements, recorded in different mammals, indicate that both sides of the brain are used for different purposes, many details still need to be specified – and dogs are no exception," he said.
However, given the ease with which their behaviours can be recorded, it will probably not take long before we understand why their tail sometimes moves on one side and sometimes on the other.
